Part 2

By 2022, the Ummed brand had moved from yellow paper labels to printed cardboard boxes.

The incense sticks were sold in three states, the medical kits distributed to ninety-two municipal health centers, the sanitary pads manufactured in three separate units near Barasat.

The business papers wrote the numbers.

*Seventy-six hundred crore.*

Vikram didn't read the papers.

He still slept in the side room of the Bagbazar house, on the same wooden bench he'd claimed when they arrived.

His clothes were still three faded cotton shirts, washed every morning at the courtyard tap.

Rehman had moved out.

He had rented an apartment in Alipore, with a security guard at the gate and a silver sedan that was cleaned twice a day by a boy he paid five hundred rupees a month.

He had been to Geneva twice for NGO conferences.

His white kurtas were silk now, the canvas shoes replaced by black leather loafers that had no mud on the soles.

"You should come to the Alipore house, uncle," Rehman had told him once. "It has air conditioning. The summer is bad for your lungs."

"My lungs are used to the neem leaves," Vikram said.

---

The celebration party was held in the lawn of a heritage hotel near the river.

Sarita had returned from New York.

She had successfully set up the US fundraising branch, Punarjeevan International, which had raised six million dollars in its first quarter.

The lawn was lit with small yellow bulbs hung from the mango trees.

Seventy people.

Three local MLAs.

Two bank directors.

A group of journalists from the business desks.

Sarita sat in a cane armchair near the food table, her walking stick leaning against her knee.

She looked thinner, but her eyes were bright.

"The numbers are huge, Vikram," she said, as he stood beside her.

"Yes," Vikram said.

"Rehman did it. He worked eighteen hours a day when I was in New York. He didn't sleep for a week during the Barasat license crisis."

"I know," Vikram said.

A local MLA approached, holding a glass of apple juice.

"Ahuja saab," he said, bowing slightly to Vikram. "Congratulations. What a massive vision. From Odisha to this. Only an Ahuja could have built a service empire this large."

Vikram didn't correct him.

He had tried correcting people for five years.

They simply smiled, nodded, and went on writing *Ahuja* in the reports anyway.

Rehman was standing three feet away, talking to a bank manager.

His glass was whiskey, the ice cubes clicking against the crystal.

He had heard the MLA.

He didn't turn.

But his shoulders went rigid under his silk kurta, his hand tightening around the glass until his knuckles went white.

---

The terrace of the hotel was dark.

Vikram had gone up to escape the noise of the catering staff cleaning plates.

The river Hooghly was visible between the warehouses, the water black, reflecting the yellow lamps of the Howrah bridge.

Rehman's footsteps were heavy on the brick floor of the terrace.

He was carrying his whiskey glass. It was empty.

"They only see you," Rehman said.

His voice was thick. The smell of alcohol was strong, mixing with the damp smell of river mud.

"Rehman," Vikram said.

"No," the boy said, walking closer. "Don't say it. Don't say 'it doesn't matter.' It matters to me."

He looked at the river.

"I did the licenses. I did the banking. I did the travel. I lived in hotels that smelled of insecticide for three years to set up the Barasat factory."

He turned to Vikram.

His face was red in the light from the bridge, his eyes wet.

"And the MLA comes and says: *Only an Ahuja could do this.* What is an Ahuja? A name? A legacy? Because your father was rich?"

"He didn't know," Vikram said.

"Nobody knows!" Rehman shouted. His glass slipped from his fingers, hitting the brick floor and cracking with a sharp, dry sound. "I am the candle, uncle. I burn myself to give the light. And everyone turns their face to the sun."

He walked to the edge of the terrace, his hands gripping the iron railing.

"Is it because of my name? Because I am Rehman? Because my mother converted? Because we had no house in Odisha?"

Vikram stood behind him.

"You built it, Rehman. The board knows. Sarita knows."

"But the world doesn't," the boy said, his voice dropping to a whisper. "I wanted to show them. I wanted to show my mother that I am not the spare. That I can build something bigger than what Rajeev took from us."

He looked back at Vikram.

"But I can't. Not as long as you are standing in the door."

He walked past Vikram.

His loafers made a sharp, clean sound on the brick floor.

"I am going to Alipore," he said, without looking back.

Vikram stood alone on the terrace.

The broken glass of Rehman's whiskey cup was catching the light of the bridge.

The wind from the river was cold.

But as he looked at the dark water, the fourteen hundred crore and the seventy-six hundred crore felt like the same thing.

A weight he was still carrying, even when he had nothing left in his pockets.

